[{"id": 7014095, "title": "Indic, Islamic and Thai Influences [Extract of Chapter 2 from Muslim Merit-making in Thailand's Far-south]", "created_at": "2014-05-11T12:59:20.529-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/7014095/Indic_Islamic_and_Thai_Influences_Extract_of_Chapter_2_from_Muslim_Merit_making_in_Thailands_Far_south_?f_ri=981203", "dom_id": "work_7014095", "summary": "This chapter describes Patani\u2019s Indic, Islamic and Thai pasts. The argu- ment is that the Malay kerajaan of Patani was similar to\u2014rather than distinct from\u2014other port city-states on the peninsula and islands of Southeast Asia where a Sanskrit cosmopolis existed for a millennium before the earliest chapters of Islam\u2019s Southeast Asian expansion. Islam also circulated east and west of Patani through trade between the Middle East and China via the Indian Ocean. This created a range of Indian/Arab/Malay creole communities whose members played key roles in the adoption of, or adhesion to, Islam in Southeast Asian port city-states like Patani. India\u2019s importance to the arrival of Islam to the Thai/Malay peninsula relates to what Islam came to, where Islam initially came from, and who Islam came through. Rather than refer to conversion, I refer to an adhesion to, or adoption of, Islam. The impact of Thai and Islamic influences in Patani/Pattani following its defeat in 1785 is described. The details of the process through which the Malay Kingdom (SM. kerajaan) of   became the Thai Province of Pattani, including Bangkok\u2019s legislative and administrative initiatives are also provided. A central con- cern of this chapter is to highlight the fact that these developments coincided with a period of revolution and reform in the Hijaz. I describe how these developments impacted local religious life and thought through local luminaries such as Shaykh Daud Al-Fatani, Shaykh Ahmad Al-Fatani and Haji Sulong. The methodologies and contributions of present-day reformist revivalist movements are also described.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 33674643, "asset_id": 7014095, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 667449, "first_name": "Christopher", "last_name": "Joll", "domain_name": "victoria", "page_name": "ChristopherJoll", "display_name": "Christopher M Joll", "profile_url": "https://victoria.academia.edu/ChristopherJoll?f_ri=981203", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/667449/851788/1060921/s65_cm.joll.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 792, "name": "Historical Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Historical_Anthropology?f_ri=981203", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1031, "name": "Southeast Asian Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Southeast_Asian_Studies?f_ri=981203", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1234, "name": "Thai Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Thai_Studies?f_ri=981203", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 4979, "name": "Islamic Contemporary Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Islamic_Contemporary_Studies?f_ri=981203", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 5076, "name": "Sanskrit language and literature", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Sanskrit_language_and_literature?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 5453, "name": "Race and Ethnicity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Race_and_Ethnicity?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 6579, "name": "Cosmopolitanism", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Cosmopolitanism?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 6746, "name": "Southeast Asia", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Southeast_Asia?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 6921, "name": "Sanskrit", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Sanskrit?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 10096, "name": "Thailand", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Thailand?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 11150, "name": "Islamic Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Islamic_Studies?f_ri=981203"}, {"id": 12177, "name": "Thai History", "url": "https://www.acad